\begin_deeper
\begin_layout Standard
Recall the rules of working with Variance.
 Suppose 
\begin_inset Formula $k$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $m$
\end_inset

 are constants and 
\begin_inset Formula $x_{i}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $y_{i}$
\end_inset

 are variables.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
\begin_inset Formula $V(k\cdot x_{i})=k^{2}V(x_{i})$
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
\begin_inset Formula $V(k\cdot x_{i}+m\cdot y_{i})=k^{2}V(x_{i})+m^{2}V(y_{i})+2\cdot k\cdot m\cdot Cov(x_{i},y_{i})$
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula $V$
\end_inset

 is variance
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula $Cov$
\end_inset

 is covariance
\end_layout

\end_deeper
\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{frame}[containsverbatim,allowframebreaks]
\end_layout

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
frametitle{Derive $Var(
\backslash
hat{b})$}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
Make our lives simpler by beginning with the OLS estimator for 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

data in deviations
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 form:
\begin_inset Separator latexpar
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_deeper
\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\hat{\beta}_{1}=\frac{\sum x_{i}y_{i}}{\sum x_{i}^{2}}\label{eq:bhatdeviationsform}
\end{equation}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
That means we have pre-scaled 
\begin_inset Formula $x_{i}=x_{i}observed-\bar{x}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $y_{i}=y_{i}observed-\bar{y}$
\end_inset

.
 That leaves 
\begin_inset Formula $\hat{\beta}_{1}$
\end_inset

 and the 
\begin_inset Formula $Var[\hat{\beta}_{1}]$
\end_inset

 unchanged, but math is easier.
 
\end_layout

\end_deeper
\begin_layout Itemize
Start by trying to figure out the 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

true variance
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 of 
\begin_inset Formula $\hat{\beta}_{1}$
\end_inset

.
 Apply the Var() operator to both sides of (
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:bhatdeviationsform"

\end_inset

)
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
Var(\hat{\beta}_{1})=Var\left(\frac{\sum x_{i}y_{i}}{\sum x_{i}^{2}}\right)\label{varb-1}
\end{equation}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
The values of 
\begin_inset Formula $x_{i}$
\end_inset

 are not thought of as random variables.
 Instead, they are variables that are 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

fixed
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 attributes of the observations.
 (If you want 
\begin_inset Formula $x_{i}$
\end_inset

 to be a random variable, you can do that, but the math is slightly different).
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
With fixed 
\begin_inset Formula $x_{i}$
\end_inset

, the sum of 
\begin_inset Formula $x_{i}^{2}$
\end_inset

, 
\begin_inset Formula $\sum x_{i}^{2}$
\end_inset

 , is a constant, 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

just some number.
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 
\begin_inset Separator latexpar
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_deeper
\begin_layout Standard
Applying Variance rule 1, we take 
\begin_inset Formula $1/\sum x_{i}^{2}$
\end_inset

 outside the parentheses in 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "varb-1"

\end_inset

.
 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
Var(\hat{\beta}_{1})=\left(\frac{1}{\sum x_{i}^{2}}\right)^{2}Var\left(\sum x_{i}y_{i}\right)\label{varb2}
\end{equation}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\end_deeper
\begin_layout Itemize
Replace 
\begin_inset Formula $y_{i}$
\end_inset

 by 
\begin_inset Formula $\beta_{1}x_{i}+e_{i}$
\end_inset

 (recall 
\begin_inset Formula $\beta_{0}$
\end_inset

=0 with deviations form data)
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
Var(\hat{\beta}_{1})=\left(\frac{1}{\sum x_{i}^{2}}\right)^{2}Var\left(\beta_{1}\sum x_{i}^{2}+\sum x_{i}e_{i}\right)\label{varb2a}
\end{equation}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
Apply the Variance rule 2:
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{eqnarray}
Var(\hat{\beta}) & = & \left(\frac{1}{\sum x_{i}^{2}}\right)^{2}\left(Var\left(\beta_{1}\sum x_{i}^{2}\right)+Var\left(\sum x_{i}e_{i}\right)\right.\label{eq:varb3}\\
 &  & \left.+2Cov\left(\beta_{1}\cdot\sum x_{i}^{2},\sum x_{i}e_{i}\right)\right)\nonumber 
\end{eqnarray}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
Expression (
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:varb3"

\end_inset

) is our focal point.
 We want to simplify that.
\begin_inset Separator latexpar
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_deeper
\begin_layout Itemize
Use a sneaky trick to make 
\begin_inset Formula $Var(\beta_{1}\sum x_{i}^{2})$
\end_inset

 go away.
 Obviously, that is equal to:
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\beta_{1}^{2}Var(\sum x_{i}^{2}).
\]

\end_inset


\begin_inset Separator latexpar
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_deeper
\begin_layout Standard
Now, here is the trick.
 Observe: 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
Var(\sum x_{i}^{2})=0.
\]

\end_inset

How? Recall, Var() refers to variance across experiments.
 Since we are thinking of 
\begin_inset Formula $x_{i}$
\end_inset

 as 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

fixed
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

, then across experiments there is no variation in the sum of squared x's.
 That sum of squared x's is a constant.
 So its variance is 0.
\end_layout

\end_deeper
\begin_layout Itemize
Make 
\begin_inset Formula $2Cov\left(\beta_{1}\cdot\sum x_{i}^{2},\sum x_{i}e_{i}\right)$
\end_inset

 disappear.
 If 
\begin_inset Formula $k$
\end_inset

 is any constant, and x is a variable, then 
\begin_inset Formula $Cov(k,x)=0$
\end_inset

.
 Covariance between a constant and a variable equals 0.
 
\end_layout

\end_deeper
\begin_layout Itemize
Thus (
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:varb3"

\end_inset

) reduces to:
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
Var(\hat{\beta}_{1})=\left(\frac{1}{\sum x_{i}^{2}}\right)^{2}Var\left(\sum x_{i}e_{i}\right)\label{varb4}
\end{equation}

\end_inset


\begin_inset Separator latexpar
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_deeper
\begin_layout Standard
Be verbose about it.
 There's a constant times the variance of a sum:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
Var(\hat{\beta}_{1})=\left(\frac{1}{\sum x_{i}^{2}}\right)^{2}Var\left(x_{1}e_{1}+x_{2}e_{2}+x_{3}e_{3}+...x_{n}e_{n}\right)\label{varb5}
\end{equation}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Now apply rule #2 about variance.
 After a little thought, one must realize that 
\begin_inset Formula $Cov(x_{i}e_{i},x_{j}e_{j})=0$
\end_inset

 because all the error terms are 'stochastically independent' of each other
 and the x's are fixed.
 (If you don't assume the x's are fixed, you have to assume instead that
 the x's are uncorrelated with the e's).
 
\end_layout

\end_deeper
\begin_layout Itemize
After applying rule #2 and throwing away all those Covariances (which are
 0), we find:
\begin_inset Separator latexpar
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_deeper
\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
Var(\hat{\beta}_{1})=\left(\frac{1}{\sum x_{i}^{2}}\right)^{2}\left(x_{1}^{2}Var(e_{1})+x_{2}^{2}Var(e_{2})+...+x_{n}^{2}Var(e_{n})\right)\label{varb6}
\end{equation}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Since we assumed above that 
\begin_inset Formula $Var(e_{i})=\sigma^{2},$
\end_inset

 then this becomes:
\end_layout

\end_deeper
\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
Var(\hat{\beta})=\left(\frac{1}{\sum x_{i}^{2}}\right)^{2}\left(x_{1}^{2}\sigma^{2}+x_{2}^{2}\sigma^{2}+...+x_{n}^{2}\sigma^{2}\right)\label{varb7}
\end{equation}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
Var(\hat{\beta})=\left(\frac{1}{\sum x_{i}^{2}}\right)^{2}\left(\sum x_{i}^{2}\sigma^{2}\right)\label{varb8}
\end{equation}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
Var(\hat{\beta})=\left(\frac{1}{\sum x_{i}^{2}}\right)^{2}\left(\sum x_{i}^{2}\right)*\sigma^{2}\label{varb9}
\end{equation}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
Var(\hat{\beta})=\left(\frac{1}{\sum x_{i}^{2}}\right)*\sigma^{2}\label{varb10-2}
\end{equation}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Whew.
 As Batman says, 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

my work is done.
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset


\end_layout

